{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626352"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:36:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:36:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17068"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17068"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.06,0.06,0.06,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9758"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77354"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9758"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17068"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62861"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5278"},{"type":"tags","id":"5280"},{"type":"tags","id":"11187"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23166"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77354"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors (NNRTIs) are an important class of antiretroviral medications used in the treatment of Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks the nucleoside binding site on reverse transcriptase","Competes with nucleosides as alternative substrates","Directly inhibits viral DNA synthesis","Prevents reverse transcriptase assembly","Binds to an allosteric site on reverse transcriptase"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENNRTIs work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding to an allosteric site on reverse transcriptase\u003C/strong\u003E. This binding causes conformational changes in the enzyme that prevent it from functioning properly, thereby inhibiting viral replication. The binding site is distinct from the active site where nucleosides bind.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks the nucleoside binding site on reverse transcriptase\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors (NRTIs), which act at the active site of the enzyme.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetes with nucleosides as alternative substrates\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of NRTIs, which are nucleoside analogues, rather than NNRTIs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly inhibits viral DNA synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; NNRTIs act indirectly by altering enzyme structure rather than directly interfering with DNA synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents reverse transcriptase assembly\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect, as NNRTIs act on the fully formed enzyme rather than interfering with its assembly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENNRTIs are highly specific for HIV-1 reverse transcriptase and do not affect human DNA polymerases or HIV-2 reverse transcriptase. Common examples include efavirenz, nevirapine, and rilpivirine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors (NNRTIs) bind to an allosteric site on HIV reverse transcriptase to inhibit viral replication.","NNRTIs are highly specific for HIV-1 reverse transcriptase and do not affect human DNA polymerases.","Common examples of NNRTIs include efavirenz, nevirapine, and rilpivirine."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Namasivayam V, Vanangamudi M, Kramer VG, et al. The Journey of HIV-1 Non-Nucleoside Reverse Transcriptase Inhibitors (NNRTIs) from Lab to Clinic. J Med Chem. 2019;62(10):4851-4883. doi:10.1021/acs.jmedchem.8b00843"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62861"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17068"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62861"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T17:38:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T17:39:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9758"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77354"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type